<subSubSection lastPageId="35" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,1888,1951]" lastBlockId="35.[151,1436,151,573]" lastPageId="35" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1888,1914]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Niu, Zhu &amp; Kuhlmann" authorityYear="2013" box="[470,623,1888,1915]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xuezhongi">
<emphasis box="[470,623,1888,1915]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">C. xuezhongi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(the male remains unknown) is recognizable through the following combination of features: bees relatively small (HW 
<quantity box="[744,885,1925,1951]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="2.7" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="2.8" valueMin="2.7">2.7â€“2.8 mm</quantity>
), clypeus relatively sparsely punctate (i=1.0â€“2.0 complete apical band in the latter) and the T2 has a distinct basal band (T2 without basal band in the latter). Females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Niu, Zhu &amp; Kuhlmann" authorityYear="2013" box="[182,330,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xuezhongi">
<emphasis box="[182,330,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">C. xuezhongi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Niu, Zhu &amp; Kuhlmann" authorityYear="2013" box="[645,784,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inspersus">
<emphasis box="[645,784,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">C. inspersus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they can be differentiated by the malar area 0.75Ã— as long as basal width of mandible in the former (malar area 1.0Ã— as long as basal width of mandible in the latter) and the paraocular area with only pale-yellow hairs in the former (paraocular area with pale-yellow and black hairs intermixed in the latter).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
